<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-129-000  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 129 000.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Jan 29 1990 n575 p31(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Designers need PLDs to wring top performance from today's CPUs.andO;(programmable logic devices) (Speakout) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Leeder, Terry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Designers who are just beginning to feel comfortable with the mostrecent generation of CPU chips must prepare to upgrade to newchips by redesigning all other subsystems to realize the speedpotential of the new CPUs and the benefits of their addedfunctions.andP;  Designers can wait for CPU-chip vendors to providethem with the other ICs they will need, they can design their ownsolutions using SSI or MSI glue chips, or they can use theprogrammable logic device (PLD) architectures now available andmatch the PLDs to their specific needs.andP;  It is in the bestinterest of designers to use PLDs to keep their systemscompetitive in the future.andP;  Most 32-bit desktop systems need bothprogrammable array logic (PAL) devices and programmable logicarrays (PLAs) for decoding and bus interface applications.andP;  Thechallenges presented to designers by ever faster CPU chips arediscussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Gate ArraysCPUProcessor SpeedEnhancementsSystem DesignUser Needs32-BitProcessor ArchitectureTrendsProgram LogicComputer-Aided DesignProgrammable logic devices.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>